summary.seg: This manuscript contains a collection of Latin medical treatises and recipes but also three previously unrecorded recipes in Middle English against head maladies (f. 267r).

This manuscript is one of the forty-five manuscripts that bear ownership and/or user marks in the hand of Roger Marchall (d. 1477), physician to Edward IV. It is one of the eighteen manuscripts that Marchall is thought to have donated to Gonville Hall (later Gonville and Caius College), alongside other manuscripts to King's College and Peterhouse (see Voigts (1995)). Thirteen manuscripts owned or used by Marchall (and another with possible Marchall connections) have been digitised, catalogued and conserved as part of the Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries project:

References: See L. Voigts, 'A doctor and his books: the manuscripts of Roger Marchall (d. 1477)', in R. Beadle and A. J. Piper (eds.), New science out of old books: studies in manuscripts and early printed books in honour of A.I. Doyle (Aldershot, 1995) pp. 249-314

supportDesc.support: The manuscript opens with four unfoliated parchment leaves (ff. [i]-[iv], followed by 288 paper leaves, and ending with four unfoliated parchment leaves (ff. [v]-[viii])

foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, on every leaf up to f. 182 and then only at the start of a new text thereafter.

signatures.p: Quire numbers added in pencil to the right-hand lower corners of the first rectos of quires in a 20th-century hand.

note.p: A table of contents added to f. [iv] verso by Roger Marchall (d. 1477) with the heading: 'Contenta in hoc volumine sunt iste'.

binding.p: Blind-stamped and -tooled brown leather over wooden boards by J.P. Gray and Son at Cambridge in 1909 (see stamp on the inside of the upper cover).

provenance.p: Roger MarchallMarchall, Roger, (d. 1477), fellow of Peterhouse and royal physician: the table of contents with his name ('R. Marchall') inscribed below on f. [iv] verso and added headings by his hand on ff. 120r, 130r, 170r, 188r. L. Voigts, 'A doctor and his books: the manuscripts of Roger Marchall (d. 1477)', in R. Beadle and A. J. Piper (eds.), New science out of old books: studies in manuscripts and early printed books in honour of A.I. Doyle (Aldershot, 1995) pp. 249-314 (p. 271 no. 10)

history.acquisition: Perhaps donated to Gonville Hall by Roger MarchallMarchall, Roger, (d. 1477) (see Provenance) and certainly at Gonville and Caius College by 1600, when it was recorded as no. 108 in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600): a 20th-centry printed armorial bookplate pasted on the inside of the upper cover inscribed with the classmark '211 - 178'; and a (?) 17th-century armorial bookplate pasted onto f. [iv] verso, inscribed with the number '178'.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on a description by M.R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, 2 vols (Cambridge: Cambridge University Library, 1907-1908), I and Kari Anne Rand Schmidt, Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, The Index of Middle English Prose, 17 (Cambridge: Brewer, 2001).

support.material: Paper, folded in quarto, with various watermarks, including a bull's head, an orb with a cross, and two arrowheads.

signatures.p: Leaf signatures written in Arabic numerals in brown ink, in the lower right-hand corner of the recto side of the leaves in the first half of each quire. Written by the same hand as the quire signatures.

Quire signatures written in Arabic numerals in brown ink, in the lower left-hand corner of the recto side of the leaves in the first half of each quire. Written by the same hand as the leaf signatures.
